00:10:46,800 --> 00:10:48,916
that the writers' room
is a very notice-y room.

244
00:10:49,079 --> 00:10:50,956
And what does that mean?

245
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:53,634
Well, yeah, that's a paradox.

246
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:56,675
Because this is a show that...

247
00:10:58,199 --> 00:11:02,317
...celebrates the outsider,

248
00:11:02,599 --> 00:11:08,708
and criticizes the human propensity
to shun or make fun of the outsider.

249
00:11:09,280 --> 00:11:12,477
But, if you do something
unusual in the writers' room,

250
00:11:12,639 --> 00:11:15,631
like, say, trim your nails
with the office scissors,

251
00:11:15,959 --> 00:11:17,790
they don't let you forget about it.

252
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:20,355
So, it is--

253
00:11:20,560 --> 00:11:23,472
It has been compared by some, me,

254
00:11:23,639 --> 00:11:26,676
to being examined
by a monster with 20 eyes.

255
00:11:28,240 --> 00:11:31,118
One of the most amazing members
of the Big Bang production team,

256
00:11:31,280 --> 00:11:33,874
is Scott London,
who is our prop master.

257
00:11:34,040 --> 00:11:37,919
And at production meetings,
we say to Scott, things like,

258
00:11:38,079 --> 00:11:39,478
"We'll need killer robots,"

259
00:11:39,639 --> 00:11:43,552
or, "We'll need
telematic kissing-machines,"

260
00:11:43,760 --> 00:11:46,672
or, "We need giant Jenga."

261
00:11:46,999 --> 00:11:52,357
And, Scott, he'll just go, "About
how big do you see the Jenga?"

262
00:11:52,839 --> 00:11:54,067
(MELISSA CHUCKLING)
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

263
00:11:56,439 --> 00:11:59,988
"Do I need two sets? One locked in
place for a point in the game,

264
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:02,913
or do all lose?
How do you want it?"

265
00:12:03,120 --> 00:12:04,678
And then he makes giant Jenga.

266
00:12:06,159 --> 00:12:09,151
The giant Jenga actually
came from Johnny, right?

267
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:12,995
Yeah, my brother in Chicago, got a
hold of some wood and a table saw,

268
00:12:13,160 --> 00:12:14,559
and next thing we knew,

269
00:12:14,720 --> 00:12:17,712
we were playing massive
Jenga in the backyard.

270
00:12:17,879 --> 00:12:19,073
By flashlight.

271
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:22,471
And when you're the size
of my brother and l,

272
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,358
it's a dangerous game.

273
00:12:25,999 --> 00:12:28,991
-lt's played to the death.
-Pretty much.

274
00:12:29,160 --> 00:12:33,870
You need to be quick, if you're
down there at the lower tiers.

275
00:12:34,680 --> 00:12:35,396
Then he also has to make

276
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:38,319
all the Chinese meals
that we eat around the table.

277
00:12:38,480 --> 00:12:40,869
And for good or ill,

278
00:12:41,039 --> 00:12:43,633
Scott was a chef beforehand.

279
00:12:43,799 --> 00:12:46,267
And so, they're absolutely delicious.

280
00:12:46,480 --> 00:12:48,357
-MEL|SSA: So good. So good.
-They're so good.

281
00:12:48,560 --> 00:12:50,437
And we eat much too much
in between takes,

282
00:12:50,600 --> 00:12:51,635
when we really
don't need to be eating.

283
00:12:51,800 --> 00:12:53,791
MELISSA: There is a lot of eating on
the show. Is that intentional?

284
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:55,353
Do you intentionally write....?

285
00:12:55,520 --> 00:12:57,431
There's a lot of eating
in the writers' room.

286
00:12:57,560 --> 00:12:58,356
(LAUGHTER)

287
00:12:58,480 --> 00:13:01,233
"So, you know, what could they be
doing at the beginning of the scene?"

288
00:13:01,399 --> 00:13:03,037
And then we're sitting and eating.

289
00:13:03,199 --> 00:13:05,474
"Well, maybe they're eating."
Okay....

290
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:07,159
They're very brainy characters,

291
00:13:07,319 --> 00:13:08,115
so in order to make them relatable,

292
00:13:08,280 --> 00:13:10,350
we want those things that
brainy people enjoy,

293
00:13:10,519 --> 00:13:11,793
as well as regular people.

294
00:13:11,959 --> 00:13:13,153
And one of those is eating.

295
00:13:15,960 --> 00:13:17,712
MAN: Why do you pick on
geologists so much?

296
00:13:18,319 --> 00:13:19,308
(LAUGHTER)
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

297
00:13:22,360 --> 00:13:23,793
Actually, those lines
are all Jim Parsons.

298
00:13:23,959 --> 00:13:28,316
He added all that about geology,
against our wishes.

299
00:13:28,480 --> 00:13:29,310
-Yeah.
-So.

300
00:13:29,519 --> 00:13:31,874
You can admit it.
It's not really a science.

301
00:13:32,319 --> 00:13:33,547
(AUDIENCE MURMURING)

302
00:13:33,759 --> 00:13:36,398
It's a-- Come on,
it's a hobby. Right?

303
00:13:37,520 --> 00:13:39,078
lt's rock collecting, isn't it?

304
00:13:39,239 --> 00:13:39,830
I don't--

305
00:13:39,999 --> 00:13:41,148
Do-- Wait, l--

306
00:13:41,319 --> 00:13:44,595
Can l-- David, do you, at UCLA, when
you're walking through the halls,

307
00:13:44,839 --> 00:13:49,867
do the geologists stop you and
ask you what the heck is going on?

308
00:13:50,560 --> 00:13:52,630
I've had to stay out
of the Geology building.

309
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:58,118
They actually will throw rocks
at you, is my understanding.

310
00:13:58,279 --> 00:14:00,190
It's the most dangerous
science to piss off.

311
00:14:00,360 --> 00:14:03,193
That's right. "Do you know
what this is? This is feldspar!"

312
00:14:05,359 --> 00:14:06,348
"This is quartz!"

313
00:14:08,639 --> 00:14:11,199
But they're probably
not that great at throwing.

314
00:14:12,120 --> 00:14:14,190
Sorry, I can't help it.

315
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:19,037
We have a lot of geologyjokes that
we haven't put in the script yet.

316
00:14:19,199 --> 00:14:21,269
Apparently, you're
hearing them all now.

317
00:14:21,439 --> 00:14:22,838
You're only encouraging them.

318
00:14:24,720 --> 00:14:25,835
And on that note. Hi.

319
00:14:25,999 --> 00:14:28,718
MAN: Are we ever going to see
the Koothrappalis?

320
00:14:28,879 --> 00:14:30,107
I think it's entirely possible.

321
00:14:30,319 --> 00:14:31,718
-Yeah, we've talked about it.
-Sure.

322
00:14:31,920 --> 00:14:34,195
It hasn't happened yet, but we've
definitely talked about it.

323
00:14:34,960 --> 00:14:36,791
MELISSA: Will we ever see
Mrs. Wolowitz?

324
00:14:37,199 --> 00:14:40,077
-We've seen--
-We've seen glimpses of her.

325
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:41,798
-Will we see--?
-Like Big Foot.

326
00:14:41,999 --> 00:14:43,068
Yes.

327
00:14:45,159 --> 00:14:46,717
Will we see more of her?

328
00:14:46,879 --> 00:14:49,029
So there's a lot of her to see...

329
00:14:49,439 --> 00:14:50,588
So, we could show parts of her,

330
00:14:50,680 --> 00:14:51,874
and really drag that out
for a long time--

331
00:14:52,079 --> 00:14:54,547
They need to make
wider screen televisions.

332
00:14:54,720 --> 00:14:57,075
It's always thrilling
to play a character,

333
00:14:57,240 --> 00:14:59,754
and then meet that
character's family members.

334
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:02,388
Much like when you sit
down with a best friend

335
00:15:02,560 --> 00:15:04,118
and you meet their parents,

336
00:15:04,280 --> 00:15:07,238
and you think, "Oh, boy,
that explains so much."

337
00:15:09,439 --> 00:15:13,796
And it's fun, and it's interesting,
and sometimes tragic.

338
00:15:14,439 --> 00:15:18,068
But always more funny,
because it's not your family.

339
00:15:18,920 --> 00:15:23,198
And-- So, it's really exciting
and insightful when you get

340
00:15:23,319 --> 00:15:26,629
to meet a character
that the writers have written

341
00:15:26,800 --> 00:15:30,554
who gives you even more backstory,
and understanding of a character

342
00:15:30,719 --> 00:15:32,914
that you've been
playing for six year, so,

343
00:15:33,080 --> 00:15:35,514
I'm looking forward to meeting
Leonard's father,

344
00:15:35,680 --> 00:15:37,352
I'm looking forward to meeting,

345
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:41,798
spending more time with his--
And we always talked about

346
00:15:41,960 --> 00:15:44,269
Sheldon and Leonard,
having the mother

347
00:15:44,439 --> 00:15:46,555
that the other wanted and needed,

348
00:15:46,720 --> 00:15:51,236
and really feeling that envy
between the two characters.

349
00:15:51,359 --> 00:15:54,590
So-- And they're both incredible
actresses obviously,

350
00:15:54,719 --> 00:15:57,950
so the more family, as far as
I'm concerned, the better.

351
00:15:58,120 --> 00:15:59,633
It just takes a story.

352
00:15:59,800 --> 00:16:02,633
It's a question that we get a lot.

353
00:16:02,800 --> 00:16:04,836
And the answer is that,

354
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:06,837
you can't say,
"We're going to do an episode

355
00:16:06,999 --> 00:16:10,708
where we meet one
of Leonard's siblings."

356
00:16:10,879 --> 00:16:14,554
You have to have a-- There has to
be a story going on with Leonard

357
00:16:14,720 --> 00:16:18,474
where meeting one of his siblings
is what you want in the story.

358
00:16:18,639 --> 00:16:22,427
It all-- All of these things
start with story.

359
00:16:22,640 --> 00:16:24,676
You have to have-- Leonard has
to be going through something,

360
00:16:24,839 --> 00:16:27,911
or the arrival of a sibling
might change something.

361
00:16:28,480 --> 00:16:29,799
MAN: What about your
personal experience

362
00:16:29,920 --> 00:16:31,512
made you want to write for this show?

363
00:16:32,079 --> 00:16:35,833
Well, I remember when lwas applying
for thisjob, I met with Bill.

364
00:16:35,999 --> 00:16:37,796
And ljust tried to do a laundry list

365
00:16:37,999 --> 00:16:42,038
of all the nerdy things
I'd ever done and that succeeded.

366
00:16:42,199 --> 00:16:46,112
And one of them was, when l was in
college, I went to a costume party,

367
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:48,191
and l dressed up
as The Doppler effect.

368
00:16:48,599 --> 00:16:49,475
And....

369
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:50,755
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

370
00:16:51,199 --> 00:16:54,430
And, since it was college, I got
increasingly drunk during the night,

371
00:16:54,639 --> 00:16:55,992
and ran around going:

372
00:16:56,120 --> 00:16:57,678
(MAKES DOPPLER EFFECT
HORN SOUND)

373
00:16:59,120 --> 00:17:01,236
And I think it was some time after
that story that Bill said,

374
00:17:01,400 --> 00:17:02,276
"You have the job."

375
00:17:02,480 --> 00:17:05,995
And also, then I was like,
"This is the best job in the world."

376
00:17:06,159 --> 00:17:11,677
Maria had a pretty good story when we
met with her for working on the--

377
00:17:11,839 --> 00:17:13,955
Yeah, right before
my interview for this job,

378
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:15,599
my husband and l were playing
a lot of World of Warcraft

379
00:17:15,760 --> 00:17:16,670
because I didn't have ajob.

380
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:20,031
And it was our anniversary,
and we didn't have any money,

381
00:17:20,240 --> 00:17:20,911
because I didn't have ajob.

382
00:17:21,079 --> 00:17:24,355
And I said, "Why don't we give
ourselves in-game presents?"

383
00:17:24,520 --> 00:17:28,035
And I really wanted a Phantom Blade,
because my rogue had just hit 30,

384
00:17:28,199 --> 00:17:29,109
or whatever that is.

385
00:17:29,280 --> 00:17:33,273
And I got him a Darkmoon Faire
Amulet, I got him a Lunacy Deck.

386
00:17:33,439 --> 00:17:35,748
And he got me real-life chocolates.

387
00:17:37,279 --> 00:17:39,554
And l was like,
"This is not what we talked about."

388
00:17:40,279 --> 00:17:41,428
(LAUGHTER)

389
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:45,715
You have the saddest story.

390
00:17:45,919 --> 00:17:50,709
Didn't you have
Dungeons 8. Dragons solo set?

391
00:17:50,879 --> 00:17:53,154
Some of us played Dungeons 8.
Dragons when we were kids a lot.

392
00:17:53,360 --> 00:17:55,191
-But if you were me--
-Nothing geeky about that.

393
00:17:55,520 --> 00:17:57,397
Well, if you had no friends,

394
00:17:57,559 --> 00:18:00,551
they made something called
Dungeons 8. Dragons solo modules,

395
00:18:00,719 --> 00:18:02,311
which you could play by yourself.

396
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:04,596
And it was like,
"Choose your own ending."

397
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:07,479
And poor little lonely, fat Steve
would be there rolling his dice,

398
00:18:07,640 --> 00:18:09,790
in his room with his solo module.

399
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,673
But now | get to work
on the show, so it all worked out.

400
00:18:13,320 --> 00:18:14,719
I still have no friends.

401
00:18:16,080 --> 00:18:18,719
Who was the most hardcore
gamer out of all of you?

402
00:18:18,880 --> 00:18:19,437
-Maria.
-Probably Maria.

403
00:18:19,599 --> 00:18:20,588
-Maria.

404
00:18:20,760 --> 00:18:21,715
-Nice.
-Yeah.

405
00:18:21,879 --> 00:18:23,676
You heard her story already, right?

406
00:18:23,840 --> 00:18:25,876
-Do you have to ask that question?
-Pretty hardcore.

407
00:18:26,120 --> 00:18:28,714
She'll take whatever is in the
environment, and play a game with it,

408
00:18:28,880 --> 00:18:31,872
whether it's a stick
or a couple of rocks.

409
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:33,229
She'll start playing with them.

410
00:18:33,400 --> 00:18:35,550
-She'll spin a hoop down the street--
-Hoops.

411
00:18:35,799 --> 00:18:37,994
MELISSA: That is the only
correct answer. Moving on.

412
00:18:39,599 --> 00:18:41,749
Who wrote out the Roommate
and Relationship Agreements?

413
00:18:41,919 --> 00:18:44,558
Because I could really
use one of those.

414
00:18:44,719 --> 00:18:46,835
We kind if pieced it together
as we've gone along.

415
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:47,876
lt's ever growing, isn't it?

416
00:18:48,040 --> 00:18:49,632
Yeah, it's a living document.

417
00:18:49,839 --> 00:18:55,391
It's a vast document, that seems to
have what you need for the story.

418
00:18:57,480 --> 00:18:59,277
Oh look, it does have that!

419
00:18:59,439 --> 00:19:00,838
I did a page of it for
Entertainmentâ€”

420
00:19:01,039 --> 00:19:01,630
Right.

421
00:19:01,839 --> 00:19:05,878
Entertainment Weekly
published a page that I did--

422
00:19:06,280 --> 00:19:08,510
And I think you could see
a page of it on the screen

423
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:11,314
in the "Shelbot" episode.

424
00:19:11,480 --> 00:19:13,948
-Yeah.
-When he flashes it to Leonard.

425
00:19:14,159 --> 00:19:16,275
There's a prop that you guys have.

426
00:19:16,439 --> 00:19:17,713
Does it have anything in it?

427
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:21,509
The binder? Oh, yeah. Again,
Scott London, the prop master.

428
00:19:21,679 --> 00:19:22,748
Yeah, it's very, very detailed.

429
00:19:22,959 --> 00:19:26,395
I've made it through a page
and a half at this point.

430
00:19:27,639 --> 00:19:29,391
Are there any inside jokes
between the writers,

431
00:19:29,559 --> 00:19:31,197
that make it into episodes?

432
00:19:32,200 --> 00:19:33,394
I'm sure there are.

433
00:19:34,199 --> 00:19:36,235
That's a very reasonable question.

434
00:19:36,719 --> 00:19:38,471
-Well, Bazinga was an inside joke.
-If we think of any--

435
00:19:38,640 --> 00:19:40,995
-Bazinga was a--
-Yeah, the grapefruit.

436
00:19:41,199 --> 00:19:43,076
Bazinga was a thing
that came from the room

437
00:19:43,279 --> 00:19:46,908
from Steven Engel,
who was a writer earlier on.

438
00:19:47,479 --> 00:19:51,313
Names of people, often,
names of characters are....

439
00:19:51,479 --> 00:19:54,755
Howard Wolowitz was the name of my
partner in the computer business

440
00:19:54,919 --> 00:19:55,988
when l was a programmer.

441
00:19:57,359 --> 00:19:58,712
And so, some of those things--

442
00:19:58,880 --> 00:20:00,677
There was a time when
Wolowitz was talking about

443
00:20:00,840 --> 00:20:02,114
bullies that had
bullied him in high school.

444
00:20:02,279 --> 00:20:04,110
And we were using
bullies from our past.

445
00:20:04,279 --> 00:20:05,428
-And lthink--
-This is true.

446
00:20:05,599 --> 00:20:07,078
I think Jim Reynolds
might have actually,

447
00:20:07,240 --> 00:20:08,992
he put his bully's name in,
and then asked to have it removed,

448
00:20:09,199 --> 00:20:11,076
-because he was afraid.
-The next day.

449
00:20:11,439 --> 00:20:12,667
(LAUGHTER)

450
00:20:12,919 --> 00:20:13,829
That's a good bully.

451
00:20:13,999 --> 00:20:15,717
That's a bully who
was good at his job.

452
00:20:15,880 --> 00:20:17,233
-l'm so desperate--
-To terrify this guy.

453
00:20:17,400 --> 00:20:19,391
I'm so desperate to tell
you guys the name right now,

454
00:20:19,599 --> 00:20:21,157
just to watch Jim sweat.

455
00:20:21,319 --> 00:20:22,832
Don't do it.
He was scary.

456
00:20:23,799 --> 00:20:25,755
MAN: Considering how chaotic
Comic-Con is,

457
00:20:25,919 --> 00:20:29,548
how does Sheldon handle that,
with all of his weird idiosyncrasies?

458
00:20:29,679 --> 00:20:30,270
That's a really good question.

459
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:31,879
I mean, lthink we haven't
talked about that.

460
00:20:32,080 --> 00:20:35,709
But I've got to believe that Sheldon
would have a very specific plan,

461
00:20:35,879 --> 00:20:36,675
where he would prepare--

462
00:20:36,839 --> 00:20:38,591
He would know the experience
he's going into,

463
00:20:38,799 --> 00:20:40,027
and he would have coping
mechanisms

464
00:20:40,199 --> 00:20:43,316
that he would have designed
for lines and things like that.

465
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:45,471
lt's howl handle Comic-Con.

466
00:20:46,720 --> 00:20:48,995
I had very specific coping
mechanisms.

467
00:20:49,159 --> 00:20:52,868
I bet we're not the people to ask
in this room, that question.

468
00:20:53,040 --> 00:20:54,871
I bet some of you
know the answer to that.

469
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:56,839
But I think Sheldon,

470
00:20:57,039 --> 00:20:58,438
difficult situations,
Sheldon does well

471
00:20:58,640 --> 00:21:02,713
if he knows what the situation
will be, and...

472
00:21:03,360 --> 00:21:04,634
...develops a coping strategy,
I think.

473
00:21:04,799 --> 00:21:05,948
I mean it's kind of a dull answer,

474
00:21:06,159 --> 00:21:07,717
but I think that's
how he would do it.

475
00:21:07,879 --> 00:21:08,994
I think he'd hate "cutsies."

476
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:12,351
-Oh, people who cut the line? Oh no.
-Sheldon wouldn't like that.

477
00:21:12,559 --> 00:21:17,349
Sheldon would probably believe
that there is a citizen's arrest...

478
00:21:17,799 --> 00:21:18,515
...possible.

479
00:21:18,680 --> 00:21:20,716
So, he would work
the logic this way,

480
00:21:20,839 --> 00:21:24,388
saying a line creates
an implied contract.

481
00:21:25,679 --> 00:21:29,274
He also would find it really weird
